title: Acacia rostriformis distribution
description: For sightings of Acacia rostriformis (formerly the Bacchus Marsh variant of Acacia verniciflua) - not including plantings or reveg plants. Also included are all insect species etc observed using Acacia rostriformis.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A few plants at the end of the Long Point Track at the Coimadai Creek crossing.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: 50-100 plants colonising an unnatural-looking pair of hillocks across from a cleared area near Djerriwarrh Creek.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: No plants on Djerriwarrh Walk until these, close to the creek. Three large old shrubs/small trees, plus three dead plants of similar size/age.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: The odd plant on roadsides in about 50% of the roads of Long Forest Rd.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A few plants visible over the fence in the reservoir works area. This is Coimadai Creek.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Lone plant in an otherwise empty paddock at Coimadai.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Good size population at the YMCA is a mix of remnant and planting. On roadside east of here is a roadside population with heaps of seedlings coming up.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Last plant noted travelling east on Glenmore Rd. Plants on a narrow roadside that was once a long slow slope down to Parwan Creek (cf 12230).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: First plant noted travelling east on Glenmore Rd. Plants on a narrow roadside that was once a long slow slope down to Yaloak Creek and Parwan Creek (cf 12231).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Last plants down the Moonah Track. None visible looking down to Djerriwarrh Creek.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Good population on Moonah Drive, especially in the dip in the road at a dry creek bed. Population continues down a walk down to Djerriwarrh Creek.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Overlooking Korkuperrimul Creek. Relatively large population here (Triassic Park) where this wattle is the dominant species. The largest leaves (phyllodes) I've seen on the species.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A few plants scattered along Tramway Lane, up the hill from Triassic Park, along the highly disturbed roadside. This escarpment overlooks Korkuperrimul Creek.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: First plants along Camerons Rd.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Last plant seen on Centenary Walk at Werribee Gorge. See also 12203.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: First plant seen on Centenary Walk at Werribee Gorge. See also 12204.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Only 3 plants spotted along the length of the Aqueduct Walk to the rock cables.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A few hundred plants dominating on the top of the Werribee Gorge escarpment in a narrow roadside area next to the train line (looks like a disturbed area).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Just one plant at this location - close to the location of a larger population at observation 12173.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: This is the most northerly plant I found on Camerons Rd (actually on White Lane).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: This is the first plant you see along Russells Rd travelling from the Gisborne-Bacchus Marsh Rd.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Plants dotted at intervals all along this section of Camerons Rd but mostly only a 4m or so wide roadside remaining.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Just one plant spotted on a part of the walk from Mackenzies Flat Picnic Area. One of the best specimens I've seen at 6m+.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Walking south on Coimadai Creek Track these are the first plants seen (about 8 plants), then similar-sized clusters of plants seen every 100m or so up to observation 12067. Always within a few metres of the creek, mostly on the other side from the track.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Walking south along Coimadai Creek this is the last cluster of plants seen before the track ran out. 5ish clusters from observation 12068 occur every 100m or so. Always within a few metres of the creek, mostly on the other side of the creek from the track

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Just a few plants at this location, the most southerly plants on Long Forest Rd.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Old, large-trunked, sprawling plant about 6m+ wide, 2m tall. Only this one plant at this location.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A dozen or so plants here.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Two 4m+ rounded shrubs visible from the fence line of this private property. Then a dozen or so plants on the main road to the south of the property heading west. No other plants seen on Hogg Rd or Chapmans Rd.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: These plants at the top of Long Forest Rd are the beginning of a large remnant patch heading south to observation 12020. Estimate would be a few hundred plants.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Pretty much the southernmost part of a largish patch extending to the top of Long Forest Road. Then little/no plants south until a few plants at observation 12019.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A seemingly outlying patch of about a dozen plants. No plants south of here on this road and no plants seen from here to about the northern entrance to Canopus Circuit (see 12020).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: One very old dead plant being replaced by 4ish new plants (estimated 2-3 year old). Similar patches (4ish plants) dotted precariously along this very narrow roadside.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Plants along roadside from park entrance to Meikles Point Picnic Area (could be reveg/planted, not sure?). The very old plant pictured is away from roads and looks remnant (other plants nearby too).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A dozen or so roadside plants either side of Djerriwarrh Creek (see also 12014).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A dozen or so roadside plants either side of Djerriwarrh Creek (see also 12015).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: A few roadside plants.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: One very old plant and one mature plant at this precise location - see other plants on these islands at 12010 and 12009). All islands here appear to be in the flood zone.

items.title: Acacia verniciflua (Bacchus Marsh variant)
items.content_text: 3 old plants at this precise location, plus 4 juvelines (probably a year old) and numerous seedlings just a few cm high (noticeably no bipinnate leaf on even the smallest plant and leaves not obviously rostriform - pic 3). See also 12009 and 12011.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: One very old plant, recently died. I've found old dead plants elsewhere with youngsters popping up around it. No new plants growing beneath this one yet. Worth a follow up next year to see if new plants germinate here. 3 more plants nearby (12010).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: One very old plant and one middle-aged plant at this location. One other plant nearby (see 12007). This location appears to be in the flood zone.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: One very old plant at this location. Two more plants nearby (see 12008). This location appears to be in the flood zone. This location is the island at Bungies Hole.

items.title: 3 ids
items.content_text: Species list for collection.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: 2 very old plants here - easily the oldest I've seen. There is an adjacent property border planting/windbreak but the two roadside plants significantly out-date planting suggesting they are remnant. Close to Seereys Rd population (see 11865-11866).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis, Xanthagrion erythroneurum
items.content_text: Numerous females around this lone, old plant. One male was also circumnavigating the plant. In pic2 the female can be seen eating a tiny insect. Leaves on this plant are 20-30mm long.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: These plants are on the Lerderderg escarpment, which is close but possibly not originally connected to the Seereys Road population (11866). 1-2 dozen mature plants at this location on a precarious roadside.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Now A. rostriformis. This population is the type locality for the species. Possibly a few hundred plants at this location.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Very hairy seedpod is an important ID feature (now A. rostriformis).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: 3 mature plants at this location.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Showing appressed hairs on raised ribs of penultimate branchlet. This is a key feature that distinguishes this species from A. verniciflua (common variant), cf. 12025.
